XIV. REGULUS.

The story of the brave death of Regulus is known to all. In the second Punic war, after he had defeated the Cartha- ginians in many battles, Regulus sailed from Sicily to Africa, and pitched his camp at Clypea. Sallying-forth5 from Clypea, he defeated the armies of the enemy ancl devastated their fields, until at last they sent an ambassador to the Lace- daemonians, to2 ask for help. The Lacedaemonians sent them Xanthippus, a very skilful leader, who defeated and captured Regulus. Then the Carthaginians sent Regulus to Rome (to see) about an exchange of prisoners, after he had sworn to return to Carthage, if he did 6 not accomplish-his- purpose.⁷ When he came to Rome, Regulus advised the Romans not to8 exchange prisoners, and although his rela- tives and friends tried to detain him, he returned to Car- thage, where he is said to have suffered a most cruel death.
